Durban - The KZN National Prosecuting Authority has confirmed that voice samples from terror suspect Farhad Hoomer were not presented when he appeared in court today. Department spokesperson Natasha Kara said the matter was adjourned to address issues regarding the obtaining of the voice samples. Hoomer, who is alleged to be the group's Kingpin and is currently out on R200 000 bail, made a brief appearance in the Verulam Magistrate's Court. He appeared on his own on Monday, but his 11 co-accused will join him in the dock during his next appearance on July 22. The 12 men, some of whom were released on warning, face charges including terrorism, murder, attempted murder, extortion, kidnapping,  contravention of the Explosives Act and arson. They are allegedly linked to a spate of bomb attacks in an around Durban and the attack on the Imam Hussein Mosque in Verulam in May 2018 that claimed the life of Abbas Essop. POST